\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 1. V. officinalis} L.,{\i  Sp. Pl.} 31 (1753). Rhizome simple, short, not very stout, sometimes stoloniferous. Stem (15-)30-150(-240) cm, usually solitary, robust, sulcate, pubescent or glabrous. All leaves usually pinnate or pinnatisect with 3-25 leaflets; leaflets linear, lanceolate or elliptical, entire or toothed. Inflorescence compound, the partial inflorescences dense. Flowers hermaphrodite, pink or white; corolla-tube 2·5-5 mm. Bracteoles about equalling fruit. Fruit 2-5 mm, hairy or glabrous. 2n = 14, 28, (49), 56. {\i  Most of Europe, but rare in the extreme south.} All except Az Bl Co Cr Fa ?Gr Sb Si.
